title: DeChent's 29 Points Not Enough As 'Cats Fall 65-54 to Maine
text:
DeChent's 29 Points Not Enough As 'Cats Fall 65-54 to Maine
1/30/2025 8:15:00 PM | Women's Basketball
DURHAM, N.H. â€“ Sophomore guard
The Wildcats fall to 8-14 on the season (2-7 America East), while the Black Bears improve to 11-10 (6-2).
Eva DeChent(Westchester, N.Y.) scored 29 points, but it wasn't enough as the University of New Hampshire women's basketball team was defeated by Maine, 65-54, on Thursday evening at Lundholm Gym.
The Wildcats fall to 8-14 on the season (2-7 America East), while the Black Bears improve to 11-10 (6-2).
Up Next
- UNH travels to Baltimore, M.D. for a matchup with UMBC on Thursday, Feb. 6 at 6:30 p.m. at Chesapeake Employers Insurance Arena.
first quarter
- The Black Bears jumped out to an early 13-4 lead as they made six of eight attempts from the field, prompting a UNH timeout with 3:37 to go in the opening frame.
- Maine took a 17-11 lead after one quarter.
second quarter
- UNH opened the second quarter with a 7-0 run to take its first lead of the game (18-17) at the 7:11 mark.
- DeChent's second 3-pointer of the game gave UNH a 23-22 edge at the media timeout (4:28).
- UNH led 28-27 before the Black Bears countered with an 8-2 run to take a 35-30 lead at halftime.
- DeChent scored 12 points in the frame for the 'Cats, getting up to 17 points through two quarters.
third quarter
- The teams traded points to open the second half. A driving layup from junior guard
Diana Eliasson(Stockholm, Sweden) got the 'Cats within three (47-44) at the 3:21 mark.
- Maine responded with an 8-1 run to take its first double digit lead of the game at 55-45.
- Sophomore guard
Maggie Cavanaugh(Point Pleasant Beach, N.J.) drew a foul and buried two free throws with less than a second left to get the Wildcats within eight at the end of the third.
fourth quarter
- The Black Bears opened the fourth quarter with a 10-1 run, making it 65-48 with 1:24 to go in the game.
- A late 6-0 run from the Wildcats wasn't enough, as Maine secured the 65-54 win.
